Appendix
Expert cross-check of the QA scenarios Q3-13
Here we continue the demonstration of QA and our analyses for questions 3 to 13. It is important to note that hallucination issues are more effectively addressed by the ChatClimate standalone version, which draws answers exclusively from IPCC AR6. This is evident in instances such as Q12, addressing maladaptation, and Q13, concerning melting glaciers. In Q12, GPT-4 offers answers related to maladaptation across various sectors. Meanwhile, in Q13, both GPT-4 and the hybrid produce hallucinations since there is no explicit statement regarding glaciers in Scotland. In these cases, we anticipate a deﬁnitive answer akin to the one provided by the ChatClimate standalone. We believe automated fact-checking methods (e.g., Vlachos and Riedel 2014; Guo, Schlichtkrull, and Vlachos 2022) can further help address hallucinations in a post-processing step where we ﬁrst perform an automated fact-check of the chatbot response before returning it to the user. To this extent, we are in the process of developing an authoritative and accurate knowledge base that can be used to fact-check domain-speciﬁc climate change related LLM responses (Stammbach, Zhang, and Ash 2023). The knowledge base will be a collection of timely peer-reviewed scientiﬁc articles and the IPCC AR6 and similar reports. We hope that this approach can help minimize the amount of hallucinations produced by a chat-based assistant.
