Q5) Have emissions reductions fallen for some countries?

Yes, emissions reductions have fallen for some countries. A growing number of countries have reduced CO2 and GHG emissions for longer than 10 years (high conﬁdence). Data up to 2018 indicates that about 24 countries have reduced territorial CO2 and GHG emissions (excluding LULUCF CO2), as well as consumption-based CO2 emissions, for at least 10 years (Page 22, IPCC AR6 WGIII Chapter02). At least 18 countries have sustained production-based GHG and consumption-based CO2 emission reductions for longer than 10 years (Page 11, IPCC AR6 WGIII SummaryForPolicymakers; Page 13, IPCC AR6 WGIII SPM). These reductions were linked to energy supply decarbonisation, energy efﬁciency gains, and energy demand reduction, which resulted from both policies and changes in economic structure (Page 11, IPCC AR6 WGIII SummaryForPolicymakers; Page 13, IPCC AR6 WGII SPM). However, the total reduction in annual GHG emissions of these countries is small (about 3.2 GtCO2-eq per yr) compared to global emissions growth observed over the last decade (Page 3, IPCC AR6 WGIII Chapter02). accuracy: 5

Yes, a growing number of countries have achieved GHG emission reductions for longer than 10 years. Data up to 2018 indicates that about 24 countries have reduced territorial CO2 and GHG emissions (excluding LULUCF CO2), as well as consumptionbased CO2 emissions, for at least 10 years. At least 18 countries have sustained production-based GHG and consumption-based CO2 emission reductions for longer than 10 years. These reductions were linked to energy supply decarbonization, energy efﬁciency gains, and energy demand reduction, which resulted from both policies and changes in economic structure. However, these reductions have only partly offset global emissions growth (Reference: IPCC AR6 WGIII Chapter02, Page:22; IPCC AR6 WGIII SummaryForPolicymakers, Page:11; IPCC AR6 WGIII SPM, Page:13; IPCC AR6 WGIII Chapter02, Page:3).
accuracy: 4

Yes, emissions reductions have fallen for some countries over the years. Various factors contribute to this, such as the implementation of climate policies, increased use of renewable energy sources, improvements in energy efﬁciency, and economic shifts. The extent of emissions reductions varies across countries, depending on their speciﬁc circumstances and efforts to combat climate change. However, it is important to note that global greenhouse gas emissions continue to rise, and more collective action is needed to achieve signiﬁcant reductions on a global scale.
